(9, 9, 'book-category', '1648-1685\r\nFollowing one family from its roots in a remote island in 17th-century Sussex, across more than two centuries to Europe and the United States, the Fairmile series illuminates how everyday women found dynasties and shape history.', 0, 3),
(10, 10, 'book-category', '1430-1568\r\nStart with The Lady of the Rivers, which is about Jacquetta of Luxemborg, who was married to the Duke of Bedford, the uncle of King Henry V. When her first husband died, she married Richard Woodville, shifting her alliance from the House of Lancaster to the House of York after the Battle of Towton. After Edward IV took the throne, Jacquetta’s daughter, Elizabeth Woodville, married him and became Queen consort to the new King of England. Don’t forget the dashes of witchcraft and magic! The novel is a historical fictionalization of one of the prominent, if often overlooked, figures in England’s civil war, known as the Wars of the Roses. The book opens in 1430, right after Henry VI is crowned King of England at only nine years old after his father, King Henry V, is killed in battle during the Hundred Years’ War.', 0, 15),
(11, 11, 'book-category', '1772-1805\r\nBeatrice Lacey, as strong-minded as she is beautiful, refuses to conform to the social customs of her time. Destined to lose her family name and beloved Wideacre estate once she is wed, Beatrice will use any means necessary to protect her ancestral heritage.', 0, 3),
(12, 12, 'book-category', '1460-1461\r\nA young woman named Isabel strives to reclaim the birthright of her family estate from her conniving brother. She and her Saracen servant Ishraq embark upon a journey to do so and run into a young novice-in-training, the “changeling” of our story, named Luca and his trusty scribe.', 0, 2),
